<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="1.[777,1374,2627,3046]" box="[778,1370,2627,2652]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[778,934,2627,2652]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
Cyclothurus 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1865" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1865" box="[1110,1366,2627,2652]" class="Mammalia" family="Cyclopedidae" genus="Cyclopes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pilosa" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dorsalis">dorsalis Gray, 1865</taxonomicName>
,
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[777,1374,2627,3046]" box="[780,959,2658,2691]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<materialsCitation box="[780,959,2658,2691]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">“Costa Rica.”</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[777,1374,2627,3046]" box="[777,1371,2698,2731]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">According to F. R. Miranda and colleagues</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[777,1374,2627,3046]" box="[779,1374,2745,2770]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">in 2017, subspecies eva, mexicanus, and dor-</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[777,1374,2627,3046]" box="[780,1371,2777,2810]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
salis are synonyms of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1865" box="[1087,1220,2777,2810]" class="Mammalia" family="Cyclopedidae" genus="Cyclopes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pilosa" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dorsalis">C. dorsalis</taxonomicName>
. Skull and
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[777,1374,2627,3046]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
pelage color of mexicanus and eva also conform well to characteristics of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1865" box="[1228,1366,2856,2889]" class="Mammalia" family="Cyclopedidae" genus="Cyclopes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pilosa" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dorsalis">C. dorsalis</taxonomicName>
, but since the molecular sample of C. dor salis consisted of a single individual from “Esmeraldas” in the forests of the Pacific coast of Ecuador, the present arrangement
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[167,1372,3052,3478]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
must be considered provisional until additional data permit complete analysis. Populations ofsilky anteaters from west of the Andes deserve further scrutiny to clarify their taxonomic status. Because 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1865" box="[559,695,3130,3163]" class="Mammalia" family="Cyclopedidae" genus="Cyclopes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pilosa" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dorsalis">C. dorsalis</taxonomicName>
has recently been elevated from subspecies to species and synonymized with eva and mexicanus, it is important to clarify its current distribution. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" targetBox="[163,755,2622,3037]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph blockId="1.[167,1372,3052,3478]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[167,343,3248,3281]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Distribution.</emphasis>
S Mexico to the inter-Andean valleys of Colombia and along the Pacific coast of Colombia and Ecuador.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[167,1372,3052,3478]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[167,411,3327,3360]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body ¢.185-215 mm, tail 170-225 mm; weight 155-275 g. Discrete skull characteristics are evident on the Central American Silky Anteater. Fronto-nasal region is not depressed, giving a straight profile. External aperture of ear is directed anteriorly. Naso-maxillary sutures diverge proximally, with very short fronto-maxillary
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[1442,2648,2306,2893]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">suture. Fronto-parietal suture has triangular or trapezoidal shape, and pterygoid bone does not overlap tympanic bulla. Color of the Central American Silky Anteater is quite different from other species: fur on body, limbs, and tail is very deeply yellow, dorsal stripe 1s irregular but distinctive, and ventralstripe is weakly marked or absent.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1444,2165,2462,2495]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[1442,2648,2306,2893]" box="[1444,2165,2462,2495]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1444,1555,2462,2495]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Habitat.</emphasis>
Mangrove swamps and tropical rainforests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1443,1944,2502,2535]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="1.[1442,2648,2306,2893]" box="[1443,1944,2502,2535]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1443,1705,2502,2535]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1443,2547,2542,2575]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="1.[1442,2648,2306,2893]" box="[1443,2547,2542,2575]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1443,1578,2542,2575]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Breeding.</emphasis>
Gestation of the Central American Silky Anteater lasts 120-150 days.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1442,2582,2581,2614]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="1.[1442,2648,2306,2893]" box="[1442,2582,2581,2614]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1442,1677,2581,2614]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Central American Silky Anteater is nocturnal and arboreal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[1442,2648,2306,2893]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1443,2136,2620,2653]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
At Barro Colorado Island, the home range of an adult male Central American Silky Anteater was 11 ha, and average home range of four adult females was 2-9 ha.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="100" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="1.[1442,2648,2306,2893]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1443,1792,2739,2772]" pageId="1" pageNumber="100">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Not assessed on The IUCN Red List. It is necessary to evaluate the conservation status of the Central American Silky Anteater because its distribution increased substantially with recent taxonomic revisions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
